{"title_page": "Mkfancy", "text_new": "{{Short description|French-bred racehorse}}\n\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Mkfancy\n| image_name = \n| caption = \n| sire = [[Makfi]]\n| grandsire = [[Dubawi]]\n| dam = Fancy Green\n| damsire = [[Muhtathir]]\n| sex = Colt\n| foaled = 28 January 2017<ref name=\"pedigree\">{{cite web|url=https://www.equineline.com/Free-5X-Pedigree.cfm/=Mkfancy%20(FR)?page_state=DISPLAY_REPORT&reference_number=10477010&registry=T&horse_name==Mkfancy%20(FR)&dam_name==Fancy%20Green%20(FR)&foaling_year=2017&include_sire_line=N&include_truenick=Y|title=Mkfancy pedigree|publisher=Equineline |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| country = France\n| colour =  [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = Marbat LLC\n| owner = Abdullah Al Maddah\n| trainer = [[Pia Brandt]]\n| record = 4: 2-1-1\n| earnings = \u00a3153,827\t\n| race = [[Criterium de Saint-Cloud]] (2019)\n|awards = \n|honours = \n|updated= \n}}\n\n'''Mkfancy''' (foaled 28 January 2017) is a French [[Thoroughbred]] racehorse. He was one of the best French juveniles of 2019 when he won two of his three races including the [[Group races|Group 1]] [[Criterium de Saint-Cloud]].\n\n==Background==\nMkfancy is a bay colt with no white [[Horse markings|markings]] bred in France by Marbat LLC, the breeding company of his owner Abdullah Al Maddah. He was sent into training with the Swedish-born Pia Brandt at [[Chantilly, Oise|Chantilly]] in France.\n\nHe was from the sixth crop of foals sired by [[Makfi]], who won the [[2000 Guineas]] and the [[Prix Jacques le Marois]] in 2010. Makfi's other foals have included [[Make Believe (horse)|Make Believe]] in Europe and the top-class Australasian winners Marky Mark ([[Manawatu Sires Produce Stakes]]), Sofia Rose ([[Australian Oaks (ATC)|Australian Oaks]]) and Bonneval ([[Underwood Stakes]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/profile/horse/752305/makfi|title=Makfi - Stud Record|work=Racing Post}}</ref>\n\nMkfancy's dam Fancy Green showed little racing ability, finishing second on her debut but running unplaced in three subsequent starts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/profile/horse/845501/fancy-green/form|title=Fancy Green race record|publisher=Racing Post}}</ref> She was a great-granddaughter of the British broodmare Martingale (foaled 1975, and a half-sister to [[Madelia (horse)|Madelia]]) who produced the [[Group races|Group 1]] winners [[Mersey (horse)|Mersey]] ([[Prix Royal Oak]]) and [[Muncie (horse)|Muncie]] ([[Prix Saint-Alary]]).<ref name=\"tbl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodlines.net/TB/Families/Family1p.htm |title=Hilarity - Family 1-p |website=Thoroughbred Bloodlines |date= |accessdate=2014-06-25}}</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n===2019: two-year-old season===\nMkfancy made his debut in an event for previously unraced juveniles over 1600 metres at [[Longchamp Racecourse]] on 1 September when he was ridden by [[Theo Bachelot]]. Starting at odds of [[Fractional odds|13/1]] in an eleven-runner field he came home third behind [[Victor Ludorum (horse)|Victor Ludorum]] and Twist, beaten five and a quarter [[Horse length|lengths]] from Twist by the winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/211/longchamp/2019-09-01/739278|title=Prix de Fontenoy result |date=1 September 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref> [[Maxime Guyon]] took the ride when the colt contested a [[maiden race]] on [[Going (horse racing)|very soft ground]] at [[Saint-Cloud Racecourse]] 26 days later and recorded his first success as he won by three lengths from thirteen opponents at odds of 3.1/1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/219/saint-cloud/2019-09-27/741284|title=Prix Louqsor result |date=27 September 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref> \n\nBachelot was back in the saddle when Mkfancy was stepped up in class and distance for the [[Group races|Group 1]] Criterium de Saint-Cloud over 2000 metres on heavy ground on 26 October. He started the 5.3/1 third favourite behind The Summit (third in the [[Prix de Conde]]), while the other six runners included Mythical, Arthur's Kingdom and Celtic High King from Ireland and Sound of Cannons and Via de Vega from England. With no previous Group or Listed winners in the field the race appeared to be a sub-standard one by Group 1 standards. Mkfancy led from the start, fought off a challenge from Mythical 300 metres from the finish and kept on well in the closing stages to win by three lengths from Arthur's Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/219/saint-cloud/2019-10-26/743601|title=Criterium de Saint-Cloud result |date=26 October 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref> After the race Pia Brandt said \"He's homebred, and it's a great feeling. We thought there was going to be a stronger pace, but he did all the work himself and Theo had confidence in the horse\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/236633/mkfancy-speeds-to-upset-win-in-criterium-de-saint-cloud|title=Mkfancy Speeds to Upset Win in Criterium de Saint-Cloud|first=Kitty|last=Trice|date=26 October 2019|website=[[The Blood-Horse]]}}</ref> \n\nIn the official rating of European two-year-olds for 2019 Mkfancy given a rating of 112 making him the third-best French juvenile behind [[Earthlight (horse)|Earthlight]] and Victor Ludorum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishhorseracing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/European-two-year-old-Classifications-2019.pdf|title=European two-year-old Classification 2019\n|date=January 2020|publisher=Britishhorseracing.com}}</ref>\n\n===2020: three-year-old season===\nMkfancy began his second campaign in the [[Listed race|Listed]] Prix Maurice Caillault over 1800 metres on the synthetic [[Polytrack]] surface at Saint-Cloud on 9 March in which he finished second of the six runners, beaten a length by the favourite Waltham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/204/chantilly/2020-03-09/753384|title=Prix Maurice Caillault result |date=9 March 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref>\n\n==Pedigree==\n{{Pedigree\n|name = Mkfancy (FR), bay colt, 2017<ref name=\"pedigree\"/>\n|inf =\n|f = [[Makfi]] (GB)<br />2007\n|m =  Fancy Green (FR)<br>2010\n|ff = [[Dubawi]] (IRE)<br>2002\n|fm = Dhelaal (GB)<br>2002\n|mf = [[Muhtathir]] (GB)<br>1995\n|mm = Fancy Stone (IRE)<br>2005\n|fff = [[Dubai Millennium]] (GB)\n|ffm = Zomaradah (GB)\n|fmf = [[Green Desert (horse)|Green Desert]] (USA)\n|fmm = Irish Valley (USA)\n|mff = [[Elmaamul]] (USA)\n|mfm = Majmu (USA)\n|mmf = [[Rainbow Quest (horse)|Rainbow Quest]] (USA)\n|mmm = Mountain Spirit\n|ffff = [[Seeking The Gold]] (USA)\n|fffm = Colorado Dancer (IRE)\n|ffmf = [[Deploy (horse)|Deploy]]\n|ffmm = Jawaher (IRE)\n|fmff = [[Danzig (horse)|Danzig]]\n|fmfm = Foreign Courier\n|fmmf = [[Irish River]] (FR)\n|fmmm = Green Valley (FR)\n|mfff = [[Diesis (horse)|Diesis]] (GB)\n|mffm = Modena\n|mfmf = [[Al Nasr (horse)|Al Nasr]] (FR)\n|mfmm = Affirmative Fable\n|mmff = [[Blushing Groom]] (FR)\n|mmfm = I Will Follow\n|mmmf = [[Royal Academy (horse)|Royal Academy]] (USA)\n|mmmm = Martingale (GB) ([[Thoroughbred breeding theories#Bruce Lowe families|Family]]: 1-p)<ref name=\"tbl\"/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2017 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in France]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in France]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 1-p]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|French-bred racehorse}}\n\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Mkfancy\n| image_name = \n| caption = \n| sire = [[Makfi]]\n| grandsire = [[Dubawi]]\n| dam = Fancy Green\n| damsire = [[Muhtathir]]\n| sex = Colt\n| foaled = 28 January 2017<ref name=\"pedigree\">{{cite web|url=https://www.equineline.com/Free-5X-Pedigree.cfm/=Mkfancy%20(FR)?page_state=DISPLAY_REPORT&reference_number=10477010&registry=T&horse_name==Mkfancy%20(FR)&dam_name==Fancy%20Green%20(FR)&foaling_year=2017&include_sire_line=N&include_truenick=Y|title=Mkfancy pedigree|publisher=Equineline |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| country = France\n| colour =  [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = Marbat LLC\n| owner = Abdullah Al Maddah\n| trainer = [[Pia Brandt]]\n| record = 4: 2-1-1\n| earnings = \u00a3153,827\t\n| race = [[Criterium de Saint-Cloud]] (2019)\n|awards = \n|honours = \n|updated= \n}}\n\n'''Mkfancy''' (foaled 28 January 2017) is a French [[Thoroughbred]] racehorse. He was one of the best French juveniles of 2019 when he won two of his three races including the [[Group races|Group 1]] [[Criterium de Saint-Cloud]].\n\n==Background==\nMkfancy is a bay colt with no white [[Horse markings|markings]] bred in France by Marbat LLC, the breeding company of his owner Abdullah Al Maddah. He was sent into training with the Swedish-born Pia Brandt at [[Chantilly, Oise|Chantilly]] in France.\n\nHe was from the sixth crop of foals sired by [[Makfi]], who won the [[2000 Guineas]] and the [[Prix Jacques le Marois]] in 2010. Makfi's other foals have included [[Make Believe (horse)|Make Believe]] in Europe and the top-class Australasian winners Marky Mark ([[Manawatu Sires Produce Stakes]]), Sofia Rose ([[Australian Oaks (ATC)|Australian Oaks]]) and Bonneval ([[Underwood Stakes]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/profile/horse/752305/makfi|title=Makfi - Stud Record|work=Racing Post}}</ref>\n\nMkfancy's dam Fancy Green showed little racing ability, finishing second on her debut but running unplaced in three subsequent starts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/profile/horse/845501/fancy-green/form|title=Fancy Green race record|publisher=Racing Post}}</ref> She was a great-grandaughter of the British broodmare Martingale (foaled 1975, and a half-sister to [[Madelia (horse)|Madelia]]) who produced the [[Group races|Group 1]] winners [[Mersey (horse)|Mersey]] ([[Prix Royal Oak]]) and [[Muncie (horse)|Muncie]] ([[Prix Saint-Alary]]).<ref name=\"tbl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodlines.net/TB/Families/Family1p.htm |title=Hilarity - Family 1-p |website=Thoroughbred Bloodlines |date= |accessdate=2014-06-25}}</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n===2019: two-year-old season===\nMkfancy made his debut in an event for previously unraced juveniles over 1600 metres at [[Longchamp Racecourse]] on 1 September when he was ridden by [[Theo Bachelot]]. Starting at odds of [[Fractional odds|13/1]] in an eleven-runner field he came home third behind [[Victor Ludorum (horse)|Victor Ludorum]] and Twist, beaten five and a quarter [[Horse length|lengths]] from Twist by the winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/211/longchamp/2019-09-01/739278|title=Prix de Fontenoy result |date=1 September 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref> [[Maxime Guyon]] took the ride when the colt contested a [[maiden race]] on [[Going (horse racing)|very soft ground]] at [[Saint-Cloud Racecourse]] 26 days later and recorded his first success as he won by three lengths from thirteen opponents at odds of 3.1/1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/219/saint-cloud/2019-09-27/741284|title=Prix Louqsor result |date=27 September 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref> \n\nBachelot was back in the saddle when Mkfancy was stepped up in class and distance for the [[Group races|Group 1]] Criterium de Saint-Cloud over 2000 metres on heavy ground on 26 October. He started the 5.3/1 third favourite behind The Summit (third in the [[Prix de Conde]]), while the other six runners included Mythical, Arthur's Kingdom and Celtic High King from Ireland and Sound of Cannons and Via de Vega from England. With no previous Group or Listed winners in the field the race appeared to be a sub-standard one by Group 1 standards. Mkfancy led from the start, fought off a challenge from Mythical 300 metres from the finish and kept on well in the closing stages to win by three lengths from Arthur's Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/219/saint-cloud/2019-10-26/743601|title=Criterium de Saint-Cloud result |date=26 October 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref> After the race Pia Brandt said \"He's homebred, and it's a great feeling. We thought there was going to be a stronger pace, but he did all the work himself and Theo had confidence in the horse\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/236633/mkfancy-speeds-to-upset-win-in-criterium-de-saint-cloud|title=Mkfancy Speeds to Upset Win in Criterium de Saint-Cloud|first=Kitty|last=Trice|date=26 October 2019|website=[[The Blood-Horse]]}}</ref> \n\nIn the official rating of European two-year-olds for 2019 Mkfancy given a rating of 112 making him the third-best French juvenile behind [[Earthlight (horse)|Earthlight]] and Victor Ludorum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishhorseracing.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/European-two-year-old-Classifications-2019.pdf|title=European two-year-old Classification 2019\n|date=January 2020|publisher=Britishhorseracing.com}}</ref>\n\n===2020: three-year-old season===\nMkfancy began his second campaign in the [[Listed race|Listed]] Prix Maurice Caillault over 1800 metres on the synthetic [[Polytrack]] surface at Saint-Cloud on 9 March in which he finished second of the six runners, beaten a length by the favourite Waltham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/results/204/chantilly/2020-03-09/753384|title=Prix Maurice Caillault result |date=9 March 2019|website=Racing Post}}</ref>\n\n==Pedigree==\n{{Pedigree\n|name = Mkfancy (FR), bay colt, 2017<ref name=\"pedigree\"/>\n|inf =\n|f = [[Makfi]] (GB)<br />2007\n|m =  Fancy Green (FR)<br>2010\n|ff = [[Dubawi]] (IRE)<br>2002\n|fm = Dhelaal (GB)<br>2002\n|mf = [[Muhtathir]] (GB)<br>1995\n|mm = Fancy Stone (IRE)<br>2005\n|fff = [[Dubai Millennium]] (GB)\n|ffm = Zomaradah (GB)\n|fmf = [[Green Desert (horse)|Green Desert]] (USA)\n|fmm = Irish Valley (USA)\n|mff = [[Elmaamul]] (USA)\n|mfm = Majmu (USA)\n|mmf = [[Rainbow Quest (horse)|Rainbow Quest]] (USA)\n|mmm = Mountain Spirit\n|ffff = [[Seeking The Gold]] (USA)\n|fffm = Colorado Dancer (IRE)\n|ffmf = [[Deploy (horse)|Deploy]]\n|ffmm = Jawaher (IRE)\n|fmff = [[Danzig (horse)|Danzig]]\n|fmfm = Foreign Courier\n|fmmf = [[Irish River]] (FR)\n|fmmm = Green Valley (FR)\n|mfff = [[Diesis (horse)|Diesis]] (GB)\n|mffm = Modena\n|mfmf = [[Al Nasr (horse)|Al Nasr]] (FR)\n|mfmm = Affirmative Fable\n|mmff = [[Blushing Groom]] (FR)\n|mmfm = I Will Follow\n|mmmf = [[Royal Academy (horse)|Royal Academy]] (USA)\n|mmmm = Martingale (GB) ([[Thoroughbred breeding theories#Bruce Lowe families|Family]]: 1-p)<ref name=\"tbl\"/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2017 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in France]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in France]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 1-p]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: grandaughter \u2192 granddaughter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mkfancy"}
{"title_page": "Up Close and Personal (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1996 American romantic drama film directed by Jon Avnet}}\n{{About|the 1996 motion picture|the Vicki Genfan album|Up Close & Personal (Vicki Genfan album)|the Angie Martinez album|Up Close and Personal (Angie Martinez album)|the Shania Twain DVD|Up! Close and Personal}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Up Close & Personal\n| image          = Up Close & Personal.jpg\n| producer       = {{ubl|Jon Avnet|[[Jordan Kerner]]|David Nicksay}}\n| director       = [[Jon Avnet]]\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Joan Didion]]|[[John Gregory Dunne]]}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''Golden Girl: The Story of Jessica Savitch''|[[Alanna Nash]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Redford]]\n* [[Michelle Pfeiffer]]\n* [[Stockard Channing]]\n* [[Joe Mantegna]]\n* [[Kate Nelligan]]\n* [[Glenn Plummer]]\n* [[James Rebhorn]]}}\n| music          = [[Thomas Newman]]\n| cinematography = [[Karl Walter Lindenlaub]]\n| editing        = Debra Neil-Fisher\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[Touchstone Pictures]]|[[Cinergi Pictures]]|[[Avnet/Kerner Productions]]}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1996|03|01}}\n| runtime        = 119 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million\n| gross          = $100,688,705\n}}\n \n'''''Up Close & Personal''''' is a 1996 American [[romantic drama film]] directed by [[Jon Avnet]], and starring [[Robert Redford]] as a news director and [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] as his proteg\u00e9e, with [[Stockard Channing]], [[Joe Mantegna]], and [[Kate Nelligan]] in supporting roles.\n\nThe screenplay began as an adaptation of ''Golden Girl: The Story of Jessica Savitch'', a 1988 book by [[Alanna Nash]] that recounted the troubled life of American news anchor [[Jessica Savitch]]. The finished picture, however, was greatly altered by commercial decisions on the part of the producers, and bore little resemblance to Savitch's biography. Screenwriter [[John Gregory Dunne]], having spent eight years working on the script with his wife [[Joan Didion]], later wrote a book describing his difficult experience, titled ''[[Monster: Living Off the Big Screen]]''.\n\nThe film was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in the category of [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\", written by [[Diane Warren]] and performed by [[Celine Dion]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{More plot|date=August 2015}}\nSally \"Tally\" Atwater ([[Michelle Pfeiffer]]) is an ambitious, aspiring news reporter, who is hired by [[Miami]] local news director Warren Justice ([[Robert Redford]]) when she sends in a homemade audition tape. He carefully guides her career to new heights, all the while becoming increasingly attracted to her.\n\nTally soon rises through the ranks of network news to become successful, while Warren's once-stellar career sinks into mediocrity. Furthermore, Tally's ascension takes her away from Warren when she is forced to relocate to [[Philadelphia]]. Tally struggles at her new post, in no small part due to the hostility of veteran reporter Marcia McGrath ([[Stockard Channing]]), who jealously protects her position as the top reporter. Warren turns up to inspire Tally, and the two partners begin a new career together.\n\nHowever, on a routine assignment in a Philadelphia prison, Tally and her cameraman are taken hostage in a prison riot and forced to endure hours of intense violence. Tally covers the groundbreaking story from within the walls of the collapsing prison as Warren looks on from outside, guiding her through her first national broadcast. This incredible act of bravery leads to Tally's eagerly anticipated advancement to a national network newscaster position and the continuation of the dynamic duo's rise to fame - but shortly after, disaster strikes when Warren is killed during an assignment.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Castlist|\n*[[Robert Redford]] as Warren Justice\n*[[Michelle Pfeiffer]] as Sally \"Tally\" Atwater\n*[[Stockard Channing]] as Marcia McGrath\n*[[Joe Mantegna]] as Bucky Terranova\n*[[Kate Nelligan]] as Joanna Kennelly\n*[[Glenn Plummer]] as Ned Jackson\n*[[James Rebhorn]] as John Merino\n*[[Scott Bryce]] as Rob Sullivan\n*[[Raymond Cruz]] as Fernando Buttanda\n*[[Dedee Pfeiffer]] as Luanne Atwater\n*[[Miguel Sandoval]] as Dan Duarte\n*[[Noble Willingham]] as Buford Sells\n*[[James Karen]] as Tom Orr\n*[[Brian Markinson]] as Vic Nash\n}}\n\n==Adaptation==\nIn the spring of 1988, [[John Gregory Dunne]] and [[Joan Didion]] began writing the script for a film entitled ''Golden Girl'', based on [[Alanna Nash]]'s biography of the late [[NBC News]] anchor and reporter [[Jessica Savitch]] and financed by [[The Walt Disney Company]]. When the film was finally released in 1996, eight years later, it was known as ''Up Close & Personal'' and none of the more controversial details of Savitch's life remained, including her alleged drug abuse problems that may have caused her to deliver an incoherent live news update on national television in early October 1983.<ref name=haller>{{cite magazine |last=Haller |first=Scot|date=1983-11-07 |title=The Two Faces of a Newswoman |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20086321,00.html |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page=48 |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] | url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081114072316/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20086321,00.html |archive-date=2008-11-14 |access-date=2016-03-06 }}</ref> Other details omitted from the film included the suicide of Savitch's second husband a few months after their wedding, and her alleged bisexuality, suicide attempts, abortion, and [[domestic violence|physical abuse]] by her longtime partner [[Ron Kershaw]], a well-known news director who was the original model for the character of Warren Justice.<ref name=muddle>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/02/reviews/970302.02gelbert.html |first=Larry |last=Gelbart |title=A Beginning, a Muddle and an End |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|location=[[New York City]] |date=1997-03-02 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020203090325/http://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/02/reviews/970302.02gelbert.html |archive-date=2002-02-03 |access-date=2016-03-06}}</ref><ref name=meers>{{cite magazine |last=Meers |first=Erik Ashok |date=1996-04-16 |title=Jessica Savaged: How Hollywood Heterosexualized ''Up Close & Personal'' |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0mMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false |magazine=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |publisher=Liberation Publications Inc.  |pages=45\u201347 |access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> Savitch's death at age 36 in an automobile accident (unrelated to drugs or alcohol) was also left out of the screenplay.<ref name=haller />\n\nAccording to Dunne, who chronicled his experiences dealing with studio executives in his book ''[[Monster: Living Off the Big Screen]]'', the majority of these changes were made in order to appeal to a broader mainstream market. Producer [[Scott Rudin]] was reported to have said, when asked by a weary Dunne what the film was supposed to be, \"it's about two movie stars.\"<ref name=muddle />\n\n==Reception==\nThe film currently holds an approval rating of 31% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 35 reviews, with an average rating of 5/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/up_close_and_personal/ |title=Up Close & Personal (1996) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCritics largely ridiculed the screenplay for bearing little resemblance to the biography of [[Jessica Savitch]], which was supposed to have inspired it. [[Roger Ebert]] in the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' wrote: \"''Up Close and Personal'' is so different from the facts of Savitch's life that if [[Joan Didion|Didion]] and [[John Gregory Dunne|Dunne]] still have their first draft, they probably could sell it as a completely different movie.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite web|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19960301/REVIEWS/603010302/1023 |first=Roger |last=Ebert |title=Up Close And Personal :: rogerebert.com :: Reviews |publisher=rogerebert.suntimes.com |date=March 1, 1996}}</ref> Anita Gates in the ''[[New York Times]]'' wrote that \"it all ends up more ''[[A Star Is Born (1937 film)|A Star Is Born]]'' than ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?_r=2&res=9502E5D61F39F933A25750C0A960958260&partner=Rotten%20Tomatoes |first=Anita |last=Gates |title=Movie Review - Up Close & Personal - As Naval Engagements Go, Not a Classic |publisher=movies.nytimes.com |date=March 10, 1996}}</ref> Leonard Klady in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described it as \"''A Star Is Born'' meets ''[[The Way We Were]]'', and while discerning audiences will turn their noses up, the hoi polloi are apt to embrace this unabashedly sentimental affair and send it soaring into the box office stratosphere.\"<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117904991.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |first=Leonard |last=Klady |title=Review, Up Close & Personal |publisher=variety.com |date=February 28, 1996}}</ref>\n\n[[Desson Howe]] in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' was extremely negative about the film: \"''Up Close and Personal'', which was \"suggested\" by the Jessica Savitch biography, ''Golden Girl: The Story of Jessica Savitch'', starts out with relative promise... but then, the loooove comes through like a bad-news feed, and our marquee lovers undergo one of those unbearable montages. While an insipid, rock ballad covers the proceedings with auditory treacle, Cushion Lips ([[Michelle Pfeiffer]]) and Armchair Man ([[Robert Redford]]) walk together, laugh together, frolic in the waves with their clothes on - that sort of thing... In this movie, network executives - who depend entirely on focus groups, marketing and advertisers to inform their decisions - are painted as the moral bad guys, while Redford and the emerging Pfeiffer are the embodiment of integrity... And the fact that this is a [[Touchstone Pictures]] production - part of the marketing-obsessed, truth-sweetening [[Disney]] empire which just purchased [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] - is far too hilarious an irony to ignore.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/upclosepersonal.htm |first=Desson |last=Howe |title='Up Close & Personal' |publisher=washingtonpost.com |date=March 1, 1996}}</ref> ''[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]]'' called it a \"soppy May\u2013December romance masquerading as a deadly earnest issues movie... Blow-dried, bleached blonde-on-bland entertainment.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/81090/up_close_personal.html |title=Review: Up Close & Personal - Film - Time Out London |publisher=timeout.com |accessdate=2009-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901010827/http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/81090/up_close_personal.html# |archive-date=2010-09-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHowever, certain critics argued that the film had its merits. [[Mick LaSalle]] in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote: \"Taken on its own terms, ''Up Close and Personal'' is a fine movie. Two star images meet and enhance each other. [[Robert Redford|Redford]], as usual, plays a rugged, outdoorsy, uncompromising man of unshakable integrity who just happens to be news director at a Miami station. [[Michelle Pfeiffer|Pfeiffer]], as usual, is gorgeous, pretty, gawky and a lot tougher and smarter than she looks.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1996/09/13/DD65585.DTL |first=Mick |last=LaSalle |title=FILM REVIEW - TV News Made 'Personal' / Redford, Pfeiffer in a fine romance |publisher=sfgate.com |date=September 13, 1996}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of four stars, arguing that the \"temptations are great to mock the clich\u00e9s and melodrama in ''Up Close and Personal'', but the movie undeniably works as what it really is - a love story.\"<ref name=\"ebert\"/> ''Variety'' praised the \"chemistry\" of [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] and [[Robert Redford]], and the \"delicious and brief star turns\" of [[Stockard Channing]], [[Kate Nelligan]] and [[Noble Willingham]], concluding that the film wasn't \"as accomplished as its inspiration but, regrettably, it's the best Hollywood has to offer in the heartstring-pulling genre.\"<ref name=\"variety\"/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThe featured song, \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\", written by [[Diane Warren]] and performed by [[Celine Dion]], won the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture or Television]], and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]].<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0118055/awards |title=Up Close & Personal (1996) - Awards |publisher=imdb.com |accessdate=2009-12-17}}</ref>\n\n[[Stockard Channing]] won a [[Blockbuster Entertainment Award]] for Favorite Supporting Actress - Romance.<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2004: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]:\t\n** \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0118055}}\n* {{Mojo title|upcloseandpersonal}}\n\n{{Jon Avnet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Up Close and Personal}}\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Cinergi Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about journalism]]\n[[Category:Films about television]]\n[[Category:Films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jon Avnet]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Thomas Newman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Miami]]\n[[Category:Films set in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Touchstone Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1996 American romantic drama film directed by Jon Avnet}}\n{{About|the 1996 motion picture|the Vicki Genfan album|Up Close & Personal (Vicki Genfan album)|the Angie Martinez album|Up Close and Personal (Angie Martinez album)|the Shania Twain DVD|Up! Close and Personal}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Up Close & Personal\n| image          = Up Close & Personal.jpg\n| producer       = {{ubl|Jon Avnet|[[Jordan Kerner]]|David Nicksay}}\n| director       = [[Jon Avnet]]\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Joan Didion]]|[[John Gregory Dunne]]}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''Golden Girl: The Story of Jessica Savitch''|[[Alanna Nash]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Redford]]\n* [[Michelle Pfeiffer]]\n* [[Stockard Channing]]\n* [[Joe Mantegna]]\n* [[Kate Nelligan]]\n* [[Glenn Plummer]]\n* [[James Rebhorn]]}}\n| music          = [[Thomas Newman]]\n| cinematography = [[Karl Walter Lindenlaub]]\n| editing        = Debra Neil-Fisher\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[Touchstone Pictures]]|[[Cinergi Pictures]]|[[Avnet/Kerner Productions]]}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1996|03|01}}\n| runtime        = 119 minutes\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million\n| gross          = $100,688,705\n}}\n \n'''''Up Close & Personal''''' is a 1996 American [[romantic drama film]] directed by [[Jon Avnet]], and starring [[Robert Redford]] as a news director and [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] as his proteg\u00e9e, with [[Stockard Channing]], [[Joe Mantegna]], and [[Kate Nelligan]] in supporting roles.\n\nThe screenplay began as an adaptation of ''Golden Girl: The Story of Jessica Savitch'', a 1988 book by [[Alanna Nash]] that recounted the troubled life of American news anchor [[Jessica Savitch]]. The finished picture, however, was greatly altered by commercial decisions on the part of the producers, and bore little resemblance to Savitch's biography. Screenwriter [[John Gregory Dunne]], having spent eight years working on the script with his wife [[Joan Didion]], later wrote a book describing his difficult experience, titled ''[[Monster: Living Off the Big Screen]]''.\n\nThe film was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] in the category of [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\", written by [[Diane Warren]] and performed by [[Celine Dion]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{More plot|date=August 2015}}\nSally \"Tally\" Atwater ([[Michelle Pfeiffer]]) is an ambitious, aspiring news reporter, who is hired by [[Miami]] local news director Warren Justice ([[Robert Redford]]) when she sends in a homemade audition tape. He carefully guides her career to new heights, all the while becoming increasingly attracted to her.\n\nTally soon rises through the ranks of network news to become successful, while Warren's once-stellar career sinks into mediocrity. Furthermore, Tally's ascension takes her away from Warren when she is forced to relocate to [[Philadelphia]]. Tally struggles at her new post, in no small part due to the hostility of veteran reporter Marcia McGrath ([[Stockard Channing]]), who jealously protects her position as the top reporter. Warren turns up to inspire Tally, and the two partners begin a new career together.\n\nHowever, on a routine assignment in a Philadelphia prison, Tally and her cameraman are taken hostage in a prison riot and forced to endure hours of intense violence. Tally covers the groundbreaking story from within the walls of the collapsing prison as Warren looks on from outside, guiding her through her first national broadcast. This incredible act of bravery leads to Tally's eagerly anticipated advancement to a national network newscaster position and the continuation of the dynamic duo's rise to fame - but shortly after, disaster strikes when Warren is killed during an assignment.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Castlist|\n*[[Robert Redford]] as Warren Justice\n*[[Michelle Pfeiffer]] as Sally \"Tally\" Atwater\n*[[Stockard Channing]] as Marcia McGrath\n*[[Joe Mantegna]] as Bucky Terranova\n*[[Kate Nelligan]] as Joanna Kennelly\n*[[Glenn Plummer]] as Ned Jackson\n*[[James Rebhorn]] as John Merino\n*[[Scott Bryce]] as Rob Sullivan\n*[[Raymond Cruz]] as Fernando Buttanda\n*[[Dedee Pfeiffer]] as Luanne Atwater\n*[[Miguel Sandoval]] as Dan Duarte\n*[[Noble Willingham]] as Buford Sells\n*[[James Karen]] as Tom Orr\n*[[Brian Markinson]] as Vic Nash\n}}\n\n==Soundtrack album track listing==\n# \"[[Exhale (Shoop Shoop)]]\" - [[98 Degrees]] (5:02)\n# \"[[Let Me Entertain You (Robbie Williams song)|Let Me Entertain You (Money Train Remix)]]\" - [[will.i.am|Will.I.Am]] featuring [[SWV]] (4:23)\n# \"[[Drowning (Backstreet Boys song)|Drowning]]\" - [[New Edition|Heads Of State]] (4:51)\n# \"[[Loungin|Summer Luv]]\" - [[LL Cool J]] (5:49)\n# \"Home Again\" - [[New Edition]] (4:40)\n# \"Darlin'\" - [[Backstreet Boys]] (4:18)\n# \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\" - [[Celine Dion]] (3:39)\n# \"[[Talk to Me (Babyface song)|Talk to Me]]\" - [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]] featuring [[Eric Clapton]] (3:50)\n# \"How Many Mics\" - [[Fugees|The Fugees]] (3:21)\n# \"[[The Blast (song)|The Blast]]\" - [[Justin Timberlake]] featuring [[Wyclef Jean]] (4:09)\n# \"[[When Can I See You]]\" - [[JC Chasez]] (4:53)\n# \"Dangerous Game\" - [[Kylie Minogue]] (4:20)\n# \"[[Freak Me]]\" - [[Keith Sweat]] featuring [[Silk (band)|Silk]] (4:04)\n# \"Don't Cry Dry Your Eyes\" - The Fugees (4:04)\n\n==Adaptation==\nIn the spring of 1988, [[John Gregory Dunne]] and [[Joan Didion]] began writing the script for a film entitled ''Golden Girl'', based on [[Alanna Nash]]'s biography of the late [[NBC News]] anchor and reporter [[Jessica Savitch]] and financed by [[The Walt Disney Company]]. When the film was finally released in 1996, eight years later, it was known as ''Up Close & Personal'' and none of the more controversial details of Savitch's life remained, including her alleged drug abuse problems that may have caused her to deliver an incoherent live news update on national television in early October 1983.<ref name=haller>{{cite magazine |last=Haller |first=Scot|date=1983-11-07 |title=The Two Faces of a Newswoman |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20086321,00.html |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |page=48 |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] | url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081114072316/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20086321,00.html |archive-date=2008-11-14 |access-date=2016-03-06 }}</ref> Other details omitted from the film included the suicide of Savitch's second husband a few months after their wedding, and her alleged bisexuality, suicide attempts, abortion, and [[domestic violence|physical abuse]] by her longtime partner [[Ron Kershaw]], a well-known news director who was the original model for the character of Warren Justice.<ref name=muddle>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/02/reviews/970302.02gelbert.html |first=Larry |last=Gelbart |title=A Beginning, a Muddle and an End |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|location=[[New York City]] |date=1997-03-02 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020203090325/http://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/02/reviews/970302.02gelbert.html |archive-date=2002-02-03 |access-date=2016-03-06}}</ref><ref name=meers>{{cite magazine |last=Meers |first=Erik Ashok |date=1996-04-16 |title=Jessica Savaged: How Hollywood Heterosexualized ''Up Close & Personal'' |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0mMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false |magazine=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |location=[[Los Angeles, California]] |publisher=Liberation Publications Inc.  |pages=45\u201347 |access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> Savitch's death at age 36 in an automobile accident (unrelated to drugs or alcohol) was also left out of the screenplay.<ref name=haller />\n\nAccording to Dunne, who chronicled his experiences dealing with studio executives in his book ''[[Monster: Living Off the Big Screen]]'', the majority of these changes were made in order to appeal to a broader mainstream market. Producer [[Scott Rudin]] was reported to have said, when asked by a weary Dunne what the film was supposed to be, \"it's about two movie stars.\"<ref name=muddle />\n\n==Reception==\nThe film currently holds an approval rating of 31% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 35 reviews, with an average rating of 5/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/up_close_and_personal/ |title=Up Close & Personal (1996) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCritics largely ridiculed the screenplay for bearing little resemblance to the biography of [[Jessica Savitch]], which was supposed to have inspired it. [[Roger Ebert]] in the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' wrote: \"''Up Close and Personal'' is so different from the facts of Savitch's life that if [[Joan Didion|Didion]] and [[John Gregory Dunne|Dunne]] still have their first draft, they probably could sell it as a completely different movie.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite web|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19960301/REVIEWS/603010302/1023 |first=Roger |last=Ebert |title=Up Close And Personal :: rogerebert.com :: Reviews |publisher=rogerebert.suntimes.com |date=March 1, 1996}}</ref> Anita Gates in the ''[[New York Times]]'' wrote that \"it all ends up more ''[[A Star Is Born (1937 film)|A Star Is Born]]'' than ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?_r=2&res=9502E5D61F39F933A25750C0A960958260&partner=Rotten%20Tomatoes |first=Anita |last=Gates |title=Movie Review - Up Close & Personal - As Naval Engagements Go, Not a Classic |publisher=movies.nytimes.com |date=March 10, 1996}}</ref> Leonard Klady in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described it as \"''A Star Is Born'' meets ''[[The Way We Were]]'', and while discerning audiences will turn their noses up, the hoi polloi are apt to embrace this unabashedly sentimental affair and send it soaring into the box office stratosphere.\"<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117904991.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |first=Leonard |last=Klady |title=Review, Up Close & Personal |publisher=variety.com |date=February 28, 1996}}</ref>\n\n[[Desson Howe]] in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' was extremely negative about the film: \"''Up Close and Personal'', which was \"suggested\" by the Jessica Savitch biography, ''Golden Girl: The Story of Jessica Savitch'', starts out with relative promise... but then, the loooove comes through like a bad-news feed, and our marquee lovers undergo one of those unbearable montages. While an insipid, rock ballad covers the proceedings with auditory treacle, Cushion Lips ([[Michelle Pfeiffer]]) and Armchair Man ([[Robert Redford]]) walk together, laugh together, frolic in the waves with their clothes on - that sort of thing... In this movie, network executives - who depend entirely on focus groups, marketing and advertisers to inform their decisions - are painted as the moral bad guys, while Redford and the emerging Pfeiffer are the embodiment of integrity... And the fact that this is a [[Touchstone Pictures]] production - part of the marketing-obsessed, truth-sweetening [[Disney]] empire which just purchased [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] - is far too hilarious an irony to ignore.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/upclosepersonal.htm |first=Desson |last=Howe |title='Up Close & Personal' |publisher=washingtonpost.com |date=March 1, 1996}}</ref> ''[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]]'' called it a \"soppy May\u2013December romance masquerading as a deadly earnest issues movie... Blow-dried, bleached blonde-on-bland entertainment.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/81090/up_close_personal.html |title=Review: Up Close & Personal - Film - Time Out London |publisher=timeout.com |accessdate=2009-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901010827/http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/81090/up_close_personal.html# |archive-date=2010-09-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHowever, certain critics argued that the film had its merits. [[Mick LaSalle]] in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote: \"Taken on its own terms, ''Up Close and Personal'' is a fine movie. Two star images meet and enhance each other. [[Robert Redford|Redford]], as usual, plays a rugged, outdoorsy, uncompromising man of unshakable integrity who just happens to be news director at a Miami station. [[Michelle Pfeiffer|Pfeiffer]], as usual, is gorgeous, pretty, gawky and a lot tougher and smarter than she looks.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1996/09/13/DD65585.DTL |first=Mick |last=LaSalle |title=FILM REVIEW - TV News Made 'Personal' / Redford, Pfeiffer in a fine romance |publisher=sfgate.com |date=September 13, 1996}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of four stars, arguing that the \"temptations are great to mock the clich\u00e9s and melodrama in ''Up Close and Personal'', but the movie undeniably works as what it really is - a love story.\"<ref name=\"ebert\"/> ''Variety'' praised the \"chemistry\" of [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] and [[Robert Redford]], and the \"delicious and brief star turns\" of [[Stockard Channing]], [[Kate Nelligan]] and [[Noble Willingham]], concluding that the film wasn't \"as accomplished as its inspiration but, regrettably, it's the best Hollywood has to offer in the heartstring-pulling genre.\"<ref name=\"variety\"/>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nThe featured song, \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\", written by [[Diane Warren]] and performed by [[Celine Dion]], won the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture or Television]], and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]].<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0118055/awards |title=Up Close & Personal (1996) - Awards |publisher=imdb.com |accessdate=2009-12-17}}</ref>\n\n[[Stockard Channing]] won a [[Blockbuster Entertainment Award]] for Favorite Supporting Actress - Romance.<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2004: [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]:\t\n** \"[[Because You Loved Me]]\" \u2013 Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/songs400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs Nominees |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2016-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0118055}}\n* {{Mojo title|upcloseandpersonal}}\n\n{{Jon Avnet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Up Close and Personal}}\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Cinergi Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about journalism]]\n[[Category:Films about television]]\n[[Category:Films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jon Avnet]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Thomas Newman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Miami]]\n[[Category:Films set in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Touchstone Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "24.52.229.13", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSoundtrack album track listing)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Up_Close_and_Personal_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Stan Hodgson", "text_new": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n|                   name = Stan Hodgson\n|                  image = \n|                  image_size = \n|                caption = \n|              birth_name = Stanley Arthur Murray Hodgson\n|               nickname = \n| \t\tbirth_date = {{birth date|1928|05|14|df=y}}\n|           birth_place = [[Durham, England|Durham]], England\n|             death_date = {{death date and age|2015|03|25|1928|05|14|df=yes}}\n|                 height = {{convert|5|ft|10|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n|                 weight = {{convert|12|st|3|lb|kg lb|abbr=on}}\n|            ru_position = Hooker\n|        ru_amateuryears = (?)\n|        ru_amateurpoints = (?)\n|        ru_amateurclubs = [[Durham City RFC]]\n|        ru_nationalteam = [[England national rugby union team|England]]\n|       ru_nationalyears = 1960\u20131964\n|        ru_nationalcaps = 11\n|      ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n|            ru_ntupdate = \n|          ru_coachclubs = \n|          ru_coachyears = \n|         ru_coachupdate = \n|                  other = \n|             occupation = \n|                 spouse = \n|               children = \n|              relatives = \n|                 school =\n|             university = \n}}\n\n'''Stanley Arthur Murray Hodgson''' (14 May 1928 \u2013 25 March 2015) was an English rugby union player who played in the Hooker position. Hodgson played club rugby for [[Durham City RFC]], was capped eleven times for the [[England national rugby union team|England national team]], and was a member of the [[British & Irish Lions|British Lions]] team that toured in 1962. He made 72 appearances for the [[Durham County Rugby Football Union|Durham County]] representative team and played four times for the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] invitational team.\n\n==Early life==\nStanley Hodgson was born in [[Durham, England|Durham]] on 14 May 1928 to George and Mable. His mother Mable died when Stan was three months old, leaving him to be raised by his grandmother, aunts and uncles. Hodgson was educated at Whinny Hill school, and after leaving took up a job at a carpet factory. He married Doreen Smith, with whom he had four children.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/14/stan-hodgson-obituary |title=\nStan Hodgson obituary |work=The Guardian |date=2015-04-14 |first=Jim |last=McManners |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Club and representative career==\n\nHodgson played all his club games for [[Durham City RFC]]. During a long career at the club, Hodgson eventually played for all four of their senior teams, before finally stopping playing at the age of 60.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\"/> Hodgson was also selected for the [[Durham County Rugby Football Union|Durham County]] representative team, and played a total of 72 matches for the team.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes to Durham's British Lions hooker |url=\nhttps://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/12895383.tributes-durhams-british-lions-hooker/ |date=2015-04-16 |first=Mark |last=Tallentire |work=The Northern Echo |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\nHodgson made his d\u00e9but for the England national team against Wales in the [[1960 Five Nations Championship]]. At 32 years old, Hodgson kept his age a secret fearing that it would affect his chances of being selected. He played all four of England's games in the 1960 championship. In 1961, Hodgson played against South Africa during their [[1960\u201361 South Africa rugby union tour of Europe|tour of Europe]] and Wales in the [[1961 Five Nations Championship|1961 Five Nations]].<ref name=\"ESPNScrum\">{{cite web |title=Player: Stan Hodgson |url=http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/player/6470.html |work=ESPN Scrum |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nHis next appearances for the England national team came in 1962, when he again played all four of their matches in [[1962 Five Nations Championship|that year's Five Nations Championship]]. Hodgson was included in the British Lions squad for their [[1962 British Lions tour to South Africa|tour of South Africa]]. He was selected to play in their opening game of the tour against [[Rhodesia national rugby union team|Rhodesia]], but broke his leg during the match ending his playing involvement for the rest of the tour.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player Archive: Stan Hodgson |work=LionsRugby.com |url=https://www.lionsrugby.com/player?PlayGuid=SH441975 |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> Rather than heading home, he was able to stay with the touring party as a guest of the South African rugby board.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shadow Over Lions' Rugby Tour |page=4 |date=1962-05-28 |work=The Times |issue=55402}}</ref>\n\nHis final appearance for England was in the 1964 Five Nations match against Wales.<ref name=\"ESPNScrum\"/>\n\nHodgson made a total of four appearances for the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] invitational team, three during their 1960 Easter Tour and in their 1962 game against Canada.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player Archive - S.A.M. Hodgson |url=http://www.barbarianfc.co.uk/archive/profile/1670/sam-hodgson/ |publisher=Barbarian F.C. |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nHodgson was made an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in the [[1987 New Year Honours]] list \"for services to Rugby Football\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=50764 |date=30 December 1986 |page=13 |supp=1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British and Irish Lions 1962}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodgson, Stan}}\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Barbarian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:British and Irish Lions rugby union players from England]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rugby union hookers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rugby biography\n|                   name = Stan Hodgson\n|                  image = \n|                  image_size = \n|                caption = \n|              birth_name = Stanley Arthur Murray Hodgson\n|               nickname = \n| \t\tbirth_date = {{birth date|1928|05|14|df=y}}\n|           birth_place = [[Durham, England|Durham]], England\n|             death_date = {{death date and age|2015|03|25|1928|05|14|df=yes}}\n|                 height = {{convert|5|ft|10|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n|                 weight = {{convert|12|st|3|lb|kg lb|abbr=on}}\n|            ru_position = Hooker\n|        ru_amateuryears = (?)\n|        ru_amateurpoints = (?)\n|        ru_amateurclubs = [[Durham City RFC]]\n|        ru_nationalteam = [[England national rugby union team|England]]\n|       ru_nationalyears = 1960\u20131964\n|        ru_nationalcaps = 11\n|      ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n|            ru_ntupdate = \n|          ru_coachclubs = \n|          ru_coachyears = \n|         ru_coachupdate = \n|                  other = \n|             occupation = \n|                 spouse = \n|               children = \n|              relatives = \n|                 school =\n|             university = \n}}\n\n'''Stanley Arthur Murray Hodgson''' (14 May 1928 \u2013 25 March 2015) was an English rugby union player who played in the Hooker position. Hodgson played club rugby for [[Durham City RFC]], was capped eleven times for the [[England national rugby union team|England national team]], and was a member of the [[British & Irish Lions|British Lions]] team that toured in 1962. He made 72 appearances for the [[Durham County Rugby Football Union|Durham County]] representative team and played four times for the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] invitational team.\n\n==Early life==\nStanley Hodgson was born in [[Durham, England|Durham]] on 14 May 1928 to George and Mable. His mother Mable died when Stan was three months old, leaving him to be raised by his grandmother, aunts and uncles. Hodgson was educated at Whinny Hill school, and after leaving took up a job at a carpet factory. He married Doreen Smith, with whom he had four children.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/14/stan-hodgson-obituary |title=\nStan Hodgson obituary |work=The Guardian |date=2015-04-14 |first=Jim |last=McManners |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Club and representative career==\n\nHodgson played all his club games for [[Durham City RFC]]. During a long career at the club, Hodgson eventually played for all four of their senior teams, before finally stopping playing at the age of 60.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\"/> Hodgson was also selected for the [[Durham County Rugby Football Union|Durham County]] representative team, and played a total of 72 matches for the team.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes to Durham's British Lions hooker |url=\nhttps://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/12895383.tributes-durhams-british-lions-hooker/ |date=2015-04-16 |first=Mark |last=Tallentire |work=The Northern Echo |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\nHodgson made his d\u00e9but for the England national team against Wales in the [[1960 Five Nations Championship]]. At 32 years old, Hodgson kept his age a secret fearing that it would affect his chances of being selected. He played all four of England's games in the 1960 championship. In 1961, Hodgson played against South Africa during their [[1960\u201361 South Africa rugby union tour of Europe|tour of Europe]] and Wales in the [[1961 Five Nations Championship|1961 Five Nations]].<ref name=\"ESPNScrum\">{{cite web |title=Player: Stan Hodgson |url=http://www.scrum.com/scrum/rugby/player/6470.html |work=ESPN Scrum |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nHis next appearances for the England national team came in 1962, when he again played all four of their matches in [[1962 Five Nations Championship|that year's Five Nations Championship]]. Hodgson was included in the British Lions squad for their [[1962 British Lions tour to South Africa|tour of South Africa]]. He was selected to play in their opening game of the tour against [[Rhodesia national rugby union team|Rhodesia]], but broke his leg during the match ending his playing involvment for the rest of the tour.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player Archive: Stan Hodgson |work=LionsRugby.com |url=https://www.lionsrugby.com/player?PlayGuid=SH441975 |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref> Rather than heading home, he was able to stay with the touring party as a guest of the South African rugby board.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shadow Over Lions' Rugby Tour |page=4 |date=1962-05-28 |work=The Times |issue=55402}}</ref>\n\nHis final appearance for England was in the 1964 Five Nations match against Wales.<ref name=\"ESPNScrum\"/>\n\nHodgson made a total of four appearances for the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] invitational team, three during their 1960 Easter Tour and in their 1962 game against Canada.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player Archive - S.A.M. Hodgson |url=http://www.barbarianfc.co.uk/archive/profile/1670/sam-hodgson/ |publisher=Barbarian F.C. |accessdate=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nHodgson was made an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in the [[1987 New Year Honours]] list \"for services to Rugby Football\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=50764 |date=30 December 1986 |page=13 |supp=1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British and Irish Lions 1962}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodgson, Stan}}\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Barbarian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:British and Irish Lions rugby union players from England]]\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rugby union hookers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInternational career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: vment \u2192 vement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stan_Hodgson"}
{"title_page": "Walther GSP", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Walther GSP (Gebrauchs Sportpistole)\n| image= Walther_GSP.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=A Walther GSP Junior commemorating the 100th Anniversary of [[Walther Arms|Carl Walther Waffenfabrik]] in 1986.\n|origin= [[Germany]]\n|type=Target pistol\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=Thore Eldh Sweden [[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]]\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer=[[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]]\n|unit_cost=\n|production_date=1968-present\n|number=\n|variants= GSP, <br />GSP-C, <br />GSP MV, <br />GSP 25 Jahre (25th Anniversary Model), <br />GSP Atlanta (1996 Olympics Commemorative), <br />GSP Expert\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight={{convert|42.33|oz|g|abbr=on}} (.22 LR)<br />{{convert|45.15|oz|abbr=on}} (.32 S&W)<ref name=\"MGV\">{{cite book|last=Peterson|first=Philip|title=Gun Digest Book of Modern Gun Values: The Shooter's Guide to Guns 1900 to Present|edition=16th|pages =260}}</ref>\n|length={{convert|17.19|in|cm|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|part_length={{convert|4.5276|in|cm|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge=[[.22 LR]] (GSP), <br />[[.32 S&W Long]] (GSP-C)<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|caliber=\n|action=Single-Action <ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|rate=\n|velocity=\n|range=\n|max_range=\n|feed= 5-shot [[Magazine (firearms)|Magazine]]<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|sights= Fixed front, fully adjustable rear<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Walther GSP''', ''Gebrauchs Sportpistole'' (Sport Pistol for Standard Use), is a single-action, precision targetshooting [[pistol]] made in [[Germany]] by [[Walther arms|Walther Sportwaffen]].  It has the same technical base as the [[Walther OSP]] and thus is almost identical in outward appearance, albeit slightly longer and heavier than the OSP.\n\nThe GSP was introduced on the world market in 1968 and was chambered for [[.22 Long Rifle]].  At the end of 1971, Walther began offering the pistol in [[.32 S&W Long]] Wadcutter as well.  Regardless of its original caliber, conversion units for the other caliber are available and easily interchangeable.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}  The anatomical, adjustable walnut grips were also available, on order from Walther, for left-handed shooters.  In 1988, Walther introduced a fully adjustable (for pull, stop, and angle) two-stage trigger that athletes could retrofit their pistols with.\n\n==Variants==\nSome of the very early GSPs were missing the slide stop lever which wasn't incorporated until the 1970s.  The early model GSPs, from 1968 to 1977, had a manual safety catch on the left side of the frame.  This feature was omitted in 1977 because it was an unnecessary feature on a competition pistol.  Also throughout the years, the design of the ergonomic grips underwent several changes.\n\nThe GSP chambered for .32 S&W Long WC, sometime referred to as the GSP-C, was intended for use in competitions that only allowed centerfire cartridges.  In 1976, Walther offered the GSP MV, which stands for ''matt vernickelt'' (matte nickel finish).  The MV models were available in both .22 lr and .32 S&W Long calibers.\n\nIn 1992, Walther had a special limited edition of the GSP designated as the 25 Jahre (25th Anniversary Edition).  The frame of this model had a nickel finish and the bolt had a gold titanium finish.  At the time, these sold for 2,549 [[Deutsche Marks]].\n\nIn 1996, Walther produced a GSP Atlanta model commemorating the [[1996 Summer Olympic Games]] in Atlanta.  These ones also had the gold titanium finish on the bolt.\n\nToday, there is also a more accurate version available known as the '''GSP Expert''' which has a vibration-absorbing Aluminum sleeve, containing inertial dampers, around the barrel.\n\nThe Walther GSP is a popular choice for the various 25 m pistol shooting events governed by the [[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]] (some contested at the Olympic games).  The .22 short variant was used in [[rapid fire pistol]]. The .22 LR variant was used for the [[25 m Pistol]] (formerly \"Sport Pistol\"), [[25 m Standard Pistol]] while the .32 caliber variant was used in the [[25 m Center-Fire Pistol]] event.\n\nUnder the N.Y Safe Act the Walther GSP is now classified as an assault weapon under N.Y state law. It is also classified as an assault weapon under Chicago and Cook County laws due to the magazine being outside of the pistol grip.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Walther GSP-Expert 22LR 002 noBG.jpg|A current production Walther GSP Expert in .22 long rifle.\nImage:Walther_GSP_-_right.jpg|A 1986 Walther GSP Junior\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{cite book\n|last=Kersten\n|first=Manfred\n|title=Walther - A German Legend\n|publisher=Safari Press\n|year=2001\n|location=California\n|isbn=1-57157-174-4}}\n\n{{cite book\n|last=Gangarosa, Jr.\n|first=Gene\n|title=The Walther Handgun Story\n|publisher=Stoeger Publishing Company\n|year=1999\n|location=New Jersey\n|isbn=0-88317-214-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.carl-walther.de/index.php?company=walther&lang=EN&content=products&hid=1&uid=3 Carl Walther GSP product page]\n{{Walther}}\n\n[[Category:Walther semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:.22 LR pistols]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name= Walther GSP (Gebrauchs Sportpistole)\n| image= Walther_GSP.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=A Walther GSP Junior commemorating the 100th Anniversary of [[Walther Arms|Carl Walther Waffenfabrik]] in 1986.\n|origin= [[Germany]]\n|type=Target pistol\n<!-- Type selection -->\n|is_ranged=yes\n<!-- Production history -->\n|designer=Thore Eldh Sweden [[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]]\n|design_date=\n|manufacturer=[[Walther arms|Carl Walther GmbH Sportwaffen]]\n|unit_cost=\n|production_date=1968-present\n|number=\n|variants= GSP, <br />GSP-C, <br />GSP MV, <br />GSP 25 Jahre (25th Anniversary Model), <br />GSP Atlanta (1996 Olympics Commemorative), <br />GSP Expert\n<!-- General specifications -->\n|weight={{convert|42.33|oz|g|abbr=on}} (.22 LR)<br />{{convert|45.15|oz|abbr=on}} (.32 S&W)<ref name=\"MGV\">{{cite book|last=Peterson|first=Philip|title=Gun Digest Book of Modern Gun Values: The Shooter's Guide to Guns 1900 to Present|edition=16th|pages =260}}</ref>\n|length={{convert|17.19|in|cm|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|part_length={{convert|4.5276|in|cm|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|width=\n|height=\n|crew=\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications -->\n|cartridge=[[.22 LR]] (GSP), <br />[[.32 S&W Long]] (GSP-C)<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|caliber=\n|action=Single-Action <ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|rate=\n|velocity=\n|range=\n|max_range=\n|feed= 5-shot [[Magazine (firearms)|Magazine]]<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n|sights= Fixed front, fully adjustable rear<ref name=\"MGV\"/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Walther GSP''', ''Gebrauchs Sportpistole'' (Sport Pistol for Standard Use), is a single-action, precision targetshooting [[pistol]] made in [[Germany]] by [[Walther arms|Walther Sportwaffen]].  It has the same technical base as the [[Walther OSP]] and thus is almost identical in outward appearance, albeit slightly longer and heavier than the OSP.\n\nThe GSP was introduced on the world market in 1968 and was chambered for [[.22 Long Rifle]].  At the end of 1971, Walther began offering the pistol in [[.32 S&W Long]] Wadcutter as well.  Regardless of its original caliber, conversion units for the other caliber are available and easily interchangeable.  The anatomical, adjustable walnut grips were also available, on order from Walther, for left-handed shooters.  In 1988, Walther introduced a fully adjustable (for pull, stop, and angle) two-stage trigger that athletes could retrofit their pistols with.\n\n==Variants==\nSome of the very early GSPs were missing the slide stop lever which wasn't incorporated until the 1970s.  The early model GSPs, from 1968 to 1977, had a manual safety catch on the left side of the frame.  This feature was omitted in 1977 because it was an unnecessary feature on a competition pistol.  Also throughout the years, the design of the ergonomic grips underwent several changes.\n\nThe GSP chambered for .32 S&W Long WC, sometime referred to as the GSP-C, was intended for use in competitions that only allowed centerfire cartridges.  In 1976, Walther offered the GSP MV, which stands for ''matt vernickelt'' (matte nickel finish).  The MV models were available in both .22 lr and .32 S&W Long calibers.\n\nIn 1992, Walther had a special limited edition of the GSP designated as the 25 Jahre (25th Anniversary Edition).  The frame of this model had a nickel finish and the bolt had a gold titanium finish.  At the time, these sold for 2,549 [[Deutsche Marks]].\n\nIn 1996, Walther produced a GSP Atlanta model commemorating the [[1996 Summer Olympic Games]] in Atlanta.  These ones also had the gold titanium finish on the bolt.\n\nToday, there is also a more accurate version available known as the '''GSP Expert''' which has a vibration-absorbing Aluminum sleeve, containing inertial dampers, around the barrel.\n\nThe Walther GSP is a popular choice for the various 25 m pistol shooting events governed by the [[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]] (some contested at the Olympic games).  The .22 short variant was used in [[rapid fire pistol]]. The .22 LR variant was used for the [[25 m Pistol]] (formerly \"Sport Pistol\"), [[25 m Standard Pistol]] while the .32 caliber variant was used in the [[25 m Center-Fire Pistol]] event.\n\nUnder the N.Y Safe Act the Walther GSP is now classified as an assault weapon under N.Y state law. It is also classified as an assault weapon under Chicago and Cook County laws due to the magazine being outside of the pistol grip.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Walther GSP-Expert 22LR 002 noBG.jpg|A current production Walther GSP Expert in .22 long rifle.\nImage:Walther_GSP_-_right.jpg|A 1986 Walther GSP Junior\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{cite book\n|last=Kersten\n|first=Manfred\n|title=Walther - A German Legend\n|publisher=Safari Press\n|year=2001\n|location=California\n|isbn=1-57157-174-4}}\n\n{{cite book\n|last=Gangarosa, Jr.\n|first=Gene\n|title=The Walther Handgun Story\n|publisher=Stoeger Publishing Company\n|year=1999\n|location=New Jersey\n|isbn=0-88317-214-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.carl-walther.de/index.php?company=walther&lang=EN&content=products&hid=1&uid=3 Carl Walther GSP product page]\n{{Walther}}\n\n[[Category:Walther semi-automatic pistols]]\n[[Category:.22 LR pistols]]\n", "name_user": "TonartStewy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added citation needed note to sentence on calibre conversion.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walther_GSP"}
{"title_page": "Maine-et-Loire's 7th constituency", "text_new": "{{short description|Constituency of the French Fifth Republic}}\n{{Infobox French constituency\n| name                = 7th constituency of [[Maine-et-Loire]]\n| image               = MapOfMaine-et-Loires7thConstituency.png\n| caption             = Maine-et-Loire's 7th Constituency shown within [[Maine-et-Loire]].\n| member-type         = Deputy\n| member              = [[Philippe Bolo]] <ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/qui|title=577 D\u00e9put\u00e9s - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n| party-colour        = MoDem\n| member-party        = [[Democratic Movement (France)|MoDem]]\n| department          = [[Maine-et-Loire]]\n| Region              = [[Pays de la Loire]]\n| canton              = Angers Nord, Angers Nord-Ouest, Cand\u00e9, Le Lion-d'Angers, Le Louroux-B\u00e9connais, Pouanc\u00e9, Segr\u00e9\n| census-date         = 2017\n| Voters              = 77820 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/elections/carte/2017/resultats|title=Les r\u00e9sultats aux \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives de 2017 - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe 7th constituency of [[Maine-et-Loire]] ([[French language|French]]: ''Septi\u00e8me circonscription de Maine-et-Loire'') is a French legislative [[Constituency (France)|constituency]] in the Maine-et-Loire ''[[Departments of France|d\u00e9partement]]''. Like the other 576 French constituencies, it elects one [[National Assembly of France|MP]] using the [[First-past-the-post voting|first past the post]] election system with a run-off.\n\n==Description==\nThe 7th Constituency of [[Maine-et-Loire]] is situated in the north west of the department, including the north and north-western suburbs of [[Angers]].\n\nIn common with other several seats in [[Maine-et-Loire]] for example the [[Maine-et-Loire's 1st constituency|1st]], [[Maine-et-Loire's 5th constituency|5th]] and [[Maine-et-Loire's 6th constituency|6th]] this constituency had a long tradition of supporting centre right candidates. This tradition was broken at the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 election]] with the election of the [[Democratic Movement (France)|MoDem]] candidate, during which election the conservative [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans party]] secured just 38% of the second round vote.<ref>http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/elections/departement/2017/resultats/49</ref>\n\n==Assembly members==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Election !! Member !! Party\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for French Democracy/meta/color}}\" | || [[1988 French legislative election|1988]]  ||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Marc Laffineur]] || [[Union for French Democracy|UDF]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for a Popular Movement/meta/color}}\" | || [[2002 French legislative election|2002]] ||[[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for a Popular Movement/meta/color}}\" | || [[2007 French legislative election|2007]] ||[[Joseph Bosse]]||[[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for a Popular Movement/meta/color}}\" | || [[2012 French legislative election|2012]] ||[[Marc Laffineur]]||[[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Democratic Movement (France)/meta/color}}\" | || [[2017 French legislative election|2017]] || [[Philippe Bolo]] || [[Democratic Movement (France)|MoDem]]\n|}\n<ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{French National Assembly constituencies}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Category:French legislative constituencies of Maine-et-Loire|7]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Constituency of the French Fifth Republic}}\n\n{{Infobox French constituency\n| name                = 7th constituency of [[Maine-et-Loire]]\n| image               = MapOfMaine-et-Loires7thConstituency.png\n| caption             = Maine-et-Loire's 7th Constituency shown within [[Maine-et-Loire]].\n| member-type         = Deputy\n| member              = [[Philippe Bolo]] <ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/qui|title=577 D\u00e9put\u00e9s - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n| party-colour        = MoDem\n| member-party        = [[Democratic Movement (France)|MoDem]]\n| department          = [[Maine-et-Loire]]\n| Region              = [[Pays de la Loire]]\n| canton              = Angers Nord, Angers Nord-Ouest, Cand\u00e9, Le Lion-d'Angers, Le Louroux-B\u00e9connais, Pouanc\u00e9, Segr\u00e9\n| census-date         = 2017\n| Voters              = 77820 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/elections/carte/2017/resultats|title=Les r\u00e9sultats aux \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives de 2017 - Assembl\u00e9e nationale|website=www2.assemblee-nationale.fr}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe 7th constituency of [[Maine-et-Loire]] ([[French language|French]]: ''Septi\u00e8me circonscription de Maine-et-Loire'') is a French legislative [[Constituency (France)|constituency]] in the Maine-et-Loire ''[[Departments of France|d\u00e9partement]]''. Like the other 576 French constituencies, it elects one [[National Assembly of France|MP]] using the [[First-past-the-post voting|first past the post]] election system with a run-off.\n\n==Description==\nThe 7th Constituency of [[Maine-et-Loire]] is situated in the north west of the department, including the north and north-western suburbs of [[Angers]].\n\nIn common with other several seats in [[Maine-et-Loire]] for example the [[Maine-et-Loire's 1st constituency|1st]], [[Maine-et-Loire's 5th constituency|5th]] and [[Maine-et-Loire's 6th constituency|6th]] this constituency had a long tradition of supporting centre right candidates. This tradition was broken at the [[2017 French legislative election|2017 election]] with the election of the [[Democratic Movement (France)|MoDem]] candidate, during which election the conservative [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans party]] secured just 38% of the second round vote.<ref>http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/elections/departement/2017/resultats/49</ref>\n\n==Assembly Members==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Election !! Member !! Party\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for French Democracy/meta/color}}\" | || [[1988 French legislative election|1988]]  ||rowspan=\"2\"|[[Marc Laffineur]] || [[Union for French Democracy|UDF]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for a Popular Movement/meta/color}}\" | || [[2002 French legislative election|2002]] ||[[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for a Popular Movement/meta/color}}\" | || [[2007 French legislative election|2007]] ||[[Joseph Bosse]]||[[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Union for a Popular Movement/meta/color}}\" | || [[2012 French legislative election|2012]] ||[[Marc Laffineur]]||[[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] \n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Democratic Movement (France)/meta/color}}\" | || [[2017 French legislative election|2017]] || [[Philippe Bolo]] || [[Democratic Movement (France)|MoDem]]\n|}\n\n<ref name=\"assemblee-nationale.fr\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{French National Assembly constituencies}}\n\n[[Category:French legislative constituencies of Maine-et-Loire|7]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag and add authority control template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maine-et-Loire%27s_7th_constituency"}
