t he thought the songs wasn't good enough to publish. After his debut album he also started to release more songs such as Summer Vibes and Morning Sun featuring his friend Hostey.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMohammed is the youngest child of his family and has an older sister. He stated that he's proud of raising by his mom says he never felt the presence of his dad even when he used to live with them.\n", "text_old": "{{db-multiple|A7|G11}}\n{{Musician\n| background       = solo_singer\n| name             = K!DMO\n| image            = Kidmowiki.jpg\n| birth_name       = Mohammed Safari Matak\n| birth_date       = 14 July 1993\n| birth_place      = Tehran , Iran\n| genre            = Indie, R&B, Alternative Hip-Hop, Electronic\n| years_active     = 2011-present\n}}\n\n'''Mohammed Safari Matak''' ([[Persian language|Persian]] : \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0635\u0641\u0631\u06cc \u0645\u0627\u062a\u06a9 , <small>pronounced</small> [[Help:IPA/Persian|[\u043c\u043e'\u04b3\u00e6:\u043c\u00e6\u0434 \u0441\u0430'\u0444\u0430'\u0440\u0438 \u043c\u0430:\u0442\u0430\u043a];]] born 14 July 1993) known as KiDMO (stylized K!DMO) , is an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] singer , songwriter and producer \n\n== Early life ==\nMohammed Safari was born in [[Tehran|Tehran,]] [[Iran]]. He used to play [[Football]] as a professional at youth levels and his dream was becoming a pro football player when at the young ages.\n\nMohammed says his grandmother was his first inspiration to become a singer and he thinks his voice is something he inherited from her. Also he has stated he grew up listening to artists like [[Spice Girls]], [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Enrique Iglesias]] and [[Celine Dion]] by the CDs one of his cousins brought him.\n\n== Career ==\nK!DMO started producing music at the age of 12 using applications like Dance Ejay and [[FL Studio|Fl Studio]]. He started writing songs mostly in [[Persian language|Farsi]] when he was 15 and in 2011 he was planning to release his debut album in farsi but couldn't make it happen because the publishing company stole his songs.\n\nHe says he always wanted to become a international artist and write songs in [[English language|English]] and never liked the [[Iranian pop music|Persian pop]] melodies.\n\nMohammed released his debut album Confirmed-Ep on March 2016. He said that album was actually recorded on 2014 but he thought the songs wasn't good enough to publish. After his debut album he also started to release more songs such as Summer Vibes and Morning Sun featuring his friend Hostey.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMohammed is the youngest child of his family and has a older sister. He stated that he's proud of raising by his mom says he never felt the presence of his dad even when he used to live with them.\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: a international \u2192 an international,  ,  \u2192 ,  (2), a older \u2192 an older", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K!DMO"}
{"title_page": "Birjia language", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Birjia\n|nativename=''Bijori''\n|states=[[India]]\n|region=\n|ethnicity=[[Asur people|Birjia]]\n|speakers=25,000\n|date=1998\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Austroasiatic\n|fam2=[[Munda languages|Munda]]\n|fam3=North Munda\n|fam4=Kherwarian\n|fam5=Kherwari\n|iso3=bix\n|glotto=bijo1238\n|glottorefname=Bijori\n}}\n\nThe '''Birjia''' language, also known as '''Binjhia''' or '''Bijori''', is a language of [[India]].  It is commonly assumed to be a [[Munda language]] closely related to the [[Asuri language]].  However, Anderson,<ref>Anderson, Gregory D.S (ed), ''The Munda languages''. Routledge Language Family Series 3 (2008). New York: Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-32890-X}}, p. 195.</ref> based on Prasad (1961:314), suggests that Birjia (Binjhia) may be an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language]], although the Birjia are a tribe of the Asuri nation. The latter include the Asur and the Agariya.\n\n==Distribution==\nBirjia is spoken in (''Ethnologue''):\n*[[Jharkhand]]: [[Cowerdaga district]] and [[Ranchi district]]\n*[[West Bengal]]: [[Darjeeling district]] and [[Jalpaiguri district]]\n*[[Madhya Pradesh]]\n*[[Odisha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Austro-Asiatic languages}}\n\n[[Category:Munda languages]]\n\n\n{{AustroAsiatic-lang-stub}}\n{{india-culture-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Birjia\n|nativename=Bijori\n|states=[[India]]\n|region=\n|ethnicity=[[Asur people|Birjia]]\n|speakers=25,000\n|date=1998\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Austroasiatic\n|fam2=[[Munda languages|Munda]]\n|fam3=North Munda\n|fam4=Kherwarian\n|fam5=Kherwari\n|iso3=bix\n|glotto=bijo1238\n|glottorefname=Bijori\n}}\n\nThe '''Birjia''' language, also known as '''Binjhia''' or '''Bijori''', is a language of [[India]].  It is commonly assumed to be a [[Munda language]] closely related to the [[Asuri language]].  However, Anderson,<ref>Anderson, Gregory D.S (ed), ''The Munda languages''. Routledge Language Family Series 3 (2008). New York: Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-32890-X}}, p. 195.</ref> based on Prasad (1961:314), suggests that Birjia (Binjhia) may be an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language]], although the Birjia are a tribe of the Asuri nation. The latter include the Asur and the Agariya.\n\n==Distribution==\nBirjia is spoken in (''Ethnologue''):\n*[[Jharkhand]]: [[Cowerdaga district]] and [[Ranchi district]]\n*[[West Bengal]]: [[Darjeeling district]] and [[Jalpaiguri district]]\n*[[Madhya Pradesh]]\n*[[Odisha]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Austro-Asiatic languages}}\n\n[[Category:Munda languages]]\n\n\n{{AustroAsiatic-lang-stub}}\n{{india-culture-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Liggliluff", "label": "safe", "comment": "nativename in cursive", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birjia_language"}
{"title_page": "Kelty Hearts F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Kelty Hearts\n| image = KeltyHearts.png\n| fullname = Kelty Hearts Football Club\n| nickname = The Hearts,<ref name=\"Club info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/club-info/4584810883 |title=Club info |publisher=Kelty Hearts FC |accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> The Jambos<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dunfermlinepress.com/sport/14956853.Moore_the_merrier_as_Hearts_hit_three/?ref=rl&lp=4 |title=Kelty Hearts boss Thomas Courts hails Jordan Moore in Jambos win while Crossgates Primrose hit six |first=Ross |last=Hart |work=Dunfermline Press |publisher=Newsquest |date=9 December 2016 |accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1975}}<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web |url=http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/club-history/4584810886 |title=Kelty Hearts History |publisher=Kelty Hearts FC |accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n| ground = New Central Park<ref name=\"New Central Park\">{{cite web |url=http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/new-central-park/4584810887 |title=New Central Park, Kelty |publisher=Kelty Hearts FC |accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref><br />Bath Street<br />[[Kelty]]\n| capacity = 2,181 (353 seated)<ref name=\"New Central Park\"/>\n| chairman = Ian Thomson<ref name=\"Club info\"/>\n| manager = [[Barry Ferguson]]\n| mgrtitle = Manager\n| league = {{Scottish football updater|KeltyHea}}\n| season = {{Scottish football updater|KeltyHea2}}\n| position = {{Scottish football updater|KeltyHea3}}\n| website = http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/<!--Home-->\n| kit_alt1 = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = _whitesholders\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1 = 903\n| body1 = 903\n| rightarm1 = 903\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = 903\n| kit_alt2 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = _whitesholders\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = 1752B6\n| body2 = 1752B6\n| rightarm2 = 1752B6\n| shorts2 = 1752B6\n| socks2 = 1752B6\n}}\n\n'''Kelty Hearts Football Club''' are a [[Association football|football]] club based in the village of [[Kelty]] in [[Fife]], [[Scotland]]. Formed in 1975<ref name=\"History\"/> and nicknamed ''the Hearts'' and ''the Jambos'', they play their home games at New Central Park.<ref name=\"New Central Park\"/> Their home strip  colours are maroon, with white shorts and maroon socks, while their away strip colours are blue, with blue shorts and blue socks.\n\nDuring the [[2018\u201319 in Scottish football|2018\u201319 season]] Kelty Hearts competed in the [[Lowland League]], the fifth tier of the [[Scottish football league system]], having been promoted from the [[East of Scotland Football League]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KeltyHeartsFC|author=Kelty Hearts FC|number=872900346514984962|date=8 June 2017|title=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DB0qOWXXoAENZqR.jpg}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dunfermlinepress.com/sport/15773167.No_sunshine_for_Leith_as_Hearts_win_again/|title=Kelty Hearts continue perfect East of Scotland League record at Leith Athletic|newspaper=[[Dunfermline Press]]|date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43821041 |title=Kelty Hearts eye SPFL as they close in on debut season title with 100% record |first=Brian |last=McLauchlin |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=19 April 2018 |accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> The club were previously members of the Fife Junior League and the [[Scottish Junior Football East Region Super League|SJFA East Superleague]], which is the highest division of the [[Scottish Junior Football Association, East Region|East Region]] of the [[Scottish Junior Football Association]].\n\nIn December 2017 the club became a full [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] member, making them eligible to enter the [[Scottish Cup]] and move up through the senior divisions.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/kelty-hearts-confirmed-as-the-89th-scottish-fa-member-club/|title=Kelty Hearts confirmed as the 89th Scottish FA member club|publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]]|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1975, Kelty Hearts were formed as Kelty Hearts Amateur Football Club. The club turned [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior]] after only a few years to remain competitive with other local sides.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/club-history/4584810886|title=Kelty Hearts - History|publisher=Kelty Hearts|language=en|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref> \n\nKelty reached the [[Scottish Junior Cup]] final twice but were runners up both times. In 1999 they were defeated 1\u20130 by [[Kilwinning Rangers F.C.|Kilwinning Rangers]], and in 2007 they were defeated 2\u20131 after extra time by [[Linlithgow Rose F.C.|Linlithgow Rose]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_cups/6717345.stm|title=Linlithgow Rose 2-1 Kelty Hearts|date=2007-06-03|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKelty looked to move away from being a [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior]] side after winning the [[Scottish Junior Football East Region Super League|East Region Super League]] for the second time in [[2016-17 East Superleague|2017]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dunfermlinepress.com/news/15342381.Kelty_accepted_into_East_of_Scotland_League/|title=Kelty accepted into East of Scotland League|website=Dunfermline Press|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> The club applied for membership to join the [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] and in December 2017 became a full [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] member, making them eligible to enter the [[Scottish Cup]] as well as joining the [[Scottish football league system]] as a senior club.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter being accepted into and winning the [[East of Scotland Football League]] in [[2017\u201318 East of Scotland Football League|2018]], Kelty were promoted to the [[Lowland League]] (the fifth tier of the [[Scottish football league system]]) for the [[2018\u201319 in Scottish football|2018\u201319 season]] after a comprehensive 10\u20130 aggregate win over [[Threave Rovers F.C.|Threave Rovers]] in the [[2017\u201318 Lowland Football League#Lowland League play-off|promotion play-off]].<ref name=prom18>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parsreview.org/view-from-the-stands/kelty-hearts-win-promotion-to-lowland-league|title=KELTY HEARTS WIN PROMOTION TO LOWLAND LEAGUE|website=Pars Review|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dunfermlinepress.com/sport/16235040.kelty-hearts-celebrate-lowland-league-promotion/|title=The only way is up for Kelty!|website=Dunfermline Press|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nThe team had been managed since October 2013 by [[Tam Courts]] but the club reluctantly accepted his resignation as manager on 11 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/KeltyHeartsFC/status/1050492635624984576|title=Kelty Hearts Football Club on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-10-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] captain [[Barry Ferguson]] was announced as the club's new manager on 18 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/rangers-legend-barry-ferguson-agrees-13435851|title=Rangers legend Barry Ferguson agrees deal to join Kelty Hearts as manager|last=Online|first=Record Sport|date=2018-10-18|work=dailyrecord|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Lowland Football League|2019-20]] Lowland League was ended with immediate effect on 13 April 2020 due to the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] pandemic with Kelty Hearts being declared champions on a points ger game average based on the current standings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52274091|title=Kelty Hearts named champions as Lowland League called early|date=2020-04-13|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slfl.co.uk/season-ends-with-immediate-effect-kelty-hearts-crowned-as-champions/|title=Season Ends With Immediate Effect - Kelty Hearts crowned as champions|date=2020-04-13|website=Scottish Lowland League|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n== Ground ==\nKelty Hearts play their home games at New Central Park, situated just off Bath Street in [[Kelty]]. \n\nThe overall capacity of New Central Park is 2,181 and consists of two covered enclosures which can hold around 1,030 spectators in total and a seated stand with a capacity of 353.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/new-central-park/4584810887|title=Kelty Hearts - NewCentral Park|website=www.keltyhearts.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> There is a social club and a sports bar within the ground. The pitch at New Central Park has a 3G MX artificial surface, which was installed in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nonleaguescotland.org.uk/kelty.htm|title=Non League Scotland|website=nonleaguescotland.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref>\n\n[[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] Reserves also play their home games at New Central Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/scotland/dunfermline-res/44342/|title=Scotland - Dunfermline Athletic FC Reserves - Results, fixtures, squad, statistics, photos, videos and news - Soccerway|website=uk.soccerway.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref>\n\n== Supporters ==\nThe majority of supporters of Kelty Hearts come from the village of [[Kelty]] and surrounding areas in [[Fife]]. \n\nKelty are also known to attract many [[Groundhopping|groundhoppers]] due to the club's good reputation as hosts on matchdays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thefitbanomad.wordpress.com/2018/02/25/kicking-off-at-kelty/|title=Kicking Off at Kelty|last=thefitbanomad|date=2018-02-25|website=TheFitbaNomad|language=en|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Rivalries ===\nKelty share a fierce local rivalry with [[East of Scotland Football League|East of Scotland]] team [[Hill of Beath Hawthorn F.C.|Hill of Beath Hawthorn]]. \n\nBoth clubs were founded in the same year in 1975. The rivalry mainly stems from the close proximity of the two clubs and both being very successful [[Scottish Junior Football Association|junior]] sides within the Fife League. Kelty and [[Hill of Beath Hawthorn F.C.|Hill of Beath]] would often exchange Fife league title wins from year to year, also frequently meet in cup competitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dunfermlinepress.com/sport/15034481.hearts-and-haws-set-for-junior-cup-cracker/|title=Hearts and Haws set for Junior Cup cracker|website=Dunfermline Press|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref> \n\nKelty Hearts are currently in the league above [[Hill of Beath Hawthorn F.C.|Hill of Beath]], competing in the [[Lowland Football League|Lowland League]]. However, they can still face each other in some cup competitions. \n\nKelty's other rivals include [[Linlithgow Rose F.C.|Linlithgow Rose]], another successful former [[Scottish Junior Football Association, East Region|East junior]] side, who they have faced in both league and cup competitions.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nA lot of [[Scottish Junior Football Association, West Region|West junior]] teams had considered Kelty competitive rivals due to the clubs success in the [[Scottish Junior Football Association, East Region|East]] and meeting several times in the [[Scottish Junior Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irvinetimes.com/news/15113704.buffs-send-kelty-packing/|title=Buffs send Kelty packing|website=Irvine Times|language=en|access-date=2018-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==Current squad==\nAs of 4 March 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.keltyhearts.co.uk/squad/4594638185|title=Squad 18/19|website=www.keltyhearts.co.uk|access-date=2019-06-21}}</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=GK|name=Ross Sinclair|other=on loan from [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=GK|name=Ben Mackenzie|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=GK|name=Jordan Millar|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=[[Craig Reid (footballer, born 1986)|Craig Reid]]}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=[[Tam Scobbie]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=Danny Ashe|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=[[Gary Cennerazzo]]|other= [[captain (association football)|captain]]|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=[[Scott Linton]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=[[Thomas Reilly (footballer)| Thomas Reilly]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=DR Congo|pos=MF|name=Arnault Bembo|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=[[Michael Tidser]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=Ross Philp|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=[[Stephen Husband]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=[[Sean McKirdy]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=JAM|pos=MF|name=[[Chris Humphrey]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|pos=FW|name=Matty Flynn}}\n{{Fs player|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Nathan Austin]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=FW|name=Cammy Russell|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=FW|name=[[Dylan Easton]]|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=DF|name=Keir Macaulay|other=on loan at [[Glenrothes F.C.|Glenrothes]]}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=FW|name=Owen Andrew|other=on loan at [[Glenrothes F.C.|Glenrothes]]}}\n{{fs end}}\n\n===Under 20s===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|nat=SCO|pos=MF|name=Tyler McKenzie|other=|no=}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Staff==\n\n=== Coaching staff ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Manager|| [[Barry Ferguson]]\n|-\n|Assistant Manager|| [[Bob Malcolm]]\n|-\n|Coach|| Murray McDowell\n|-\n|Coach|| Stefan Winiarski\n|-\n|Physio|| Gordon Edwards\n|